For an enterprise application like this Order Tracker, deciding where to store your documents (Purchase Orders, Invoices, Proof of Deliveries) is one of the most critical architectural decisions.

Here is the breakdown of your options, including a third option which is actually the industry standard:

1. Server's Own Storage (Local Filesystem)
Currently, the app saves files directly to the server's hard drive.

The Good: Extremely fast to build. Zero API latency when saving or reading files.
The Bad: It does not scale. Modern web apps are usually deployed to cloud services (like Vercel, AWS ECS, or Render) where the server is "ephemeral"—meaning if the server restarts or scales up to handle more traffic, the local hard drive is wiped clean and all files are lost. Furthermore, if you need two servers to handle traffic, Server A won't have access to files uploaded on Server B.
Verdict: Never use this for production unless you are running a single, self-managed physical server in your own office closet (which is highly discouraged).

2. OneDrive / SharePoint (via Microsoft Graph API)
The Good: If your company's back-office team already uses Microsoft 365 heavily, saving files to OneDrive means your accountants and managers can simply open a folder in Windows Explorer and see all the Invoices nicely organized, without even logging into the Order Tracker app.
The Bad: The Microsoft Graph API is notoriously slow compared to dedicated storage APIs. It also has strict rate limits. If a vendor uploads 50 invoices at once, Microsoft might throttle your app. Setting up the server-to-server authentication (OAuth) is also notoriously complex.
Verdict: Use this ONLY IF it is an absolute business requirement that your internal non-technical staff must browse these files natively in Windows Explorer.

3. The Industry Standard: Cloud Object Storage (AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, or Azure Blob)
The Good: This is how 99% of modern web apps (including Netflix, Airbnb, and Google) store files. It is infinitely scalable, extremely cheap (fractions of a penny per gigabyte), and highly secure. Instead of routing the file through your Node.js server, you can generate a "pre-signed URL" that lets the user upload/download the file directly to the cloud, taking all the load off your server.
The Bad: Requires setting up a cloud account (like AWS or Azure) and learning a new API SDK.
Verdict: This is the strongly recommended approach.
My Recommendation as a System Designer:
If your team is already fully embedded in the Microsoft ecosystem (e.g., you use Azure and Microsoft 365), you should use Azure Blob Storage. It provides the enterprise-grade speed and scalability of AWS S3, but integrates seamlessly into your existing Microsoft billing and architecture.

If you truly want your internal staff to see the files on their desktop, you could use OneDrive, but be prepared to build a robust background queue in your code to handle API rate limits and slow upload times gracefully.

------------------///cost breakdown////-----------------

Here is a detailed cost breakdown for each of the three storage options. For context, I am estimating based on a moderate enterprise workflow where you might generate 100 GB of PDFs and images (roughly 50,000 to 100,000 documents) over time.

1. Server's Own Storage (Local Filesystem)
Storage Cost: "Free" initially, because you just use the hard drive that comes with your web server. However, if you need more space, you have to buy Block Storage (like AWS EBS or DigitalOcean Volumes), which costs roughly $0.10 per GB / month ($10/month for 100 GB).
Bandwidth Cost: Usually included in your server's monthly bandwidth cap.
Hidden Costs (High):
Serving heavy PDFs forces your web server to work harder. You will likely need to upgrade your server (e.g., moving from a $20/mo server to an $80/mo server) just to handle the traffic spikes without crashing.
You will have to pay for a separate backup service, because if the server's hard drive fails, all your business invoices are gone.

2. OneDrive / SharePoint (via Microsoft Graph API)
Storage Cost: $0 (Included) if your company already pays for Microsoft 365 Business or Enterprise licenses. Each user usually gets 1TB of OneDrive storage, and SharePoint sites get a pooled 1TB base.
API Cost: Microsoft does not charge per API call for standard Graph API usage.
Hidden Costs (Moderate):
Licensing: You may need to purchase a dedicated "Service Account" license (e.g., $10 - $20 / month) so the app has its own account to authenticate with, rather than tying it to a specific employee's personal Microsoft account.
Developer Time: The Graph API is notoriously complex to set up securely for server-to-server communication. You will pay for the extra engineering hours required to build robust error handling and rate-limit retry queues.
3. Cloud Object Storage (Azure Blob or AWS S3) — Recommended
Storage Cost: Roughly $0.02 per GB / month.
100 GB of documents = ~$2.00 / month.
1,000 GB (1 Terabyte) = ~$20.00 / month.
Bandwidth (Data Transfer) Cost: Roughly $0.08 per GB downloaded by the user. If your team and vendors download 50 GB of documents a month, that's ~$4.00 / month. Uploading files into the storage is completely free.
API Request Cost: Negligible. (e.g., $0.005 per 1,000 upload requests). It usually amounts to less than $0.10 a month.
Hidden Costs: None. It is fully managed. You don't have to back it up (it has 99.999999999% durability built-in), and it doesn't affect your web server's CPU or RAM.
Summary Verdict
If you use Azure Blob Storage or AWS S3, you will likely pay less than $5.00 a month total to securely store and serve tens of thousands of documents. It is vastly cheaper, infinitely more reliable, and performs significantly better than trying to host the files on your own server.

OneDrive is a valid alternative financially (since you likely already pay for it), but only if the business value of seeing the files directly in Windows Explorer outweighs the slightly slower app performance and increased initial development time.